Hi all,

Figured I would spread the word about some of my recent publications 
employing CPPN-NEAT for any of you that may be interested, but were 
unable to attend my presentations at GECCO and ALife.

The first two are on evolving CPPN encoded (simulated) robot 
morphologies to explore different relationships between environmental 
complexity and the complexity of evolved robots. Unlike our previous 
work in this area here robots are created out of rigid body triangular 
mesh components.

Joshua E. Auerbach and Josh C. Bongard.  On the Relationship Between 
Environmental and Morphological Complexity in Evolved Robots. 2012 
Genetic and Evolutionary Computation Conference (GECCO 2012). 
Philadelphia, PA, July, 2012.

Paper available here: 
http://www.cs.uvm.edu/~jauerbac/publications/auerbach_bongard_gecco_2012.pdf
Accompanying videos available here: http://tinyurl.com/GECCO2012-Videos

Joshua E. Auerbach and Josh C. Bongard.  On the Relationship Between 
Environmental and Mechanical Complexity in Evolved Robots. 13th 
International Conference on the Synthesis and Simulation of Living 
Systems (ALife XIII).  East Lansing, MI, July, 2012.

Paper: 
http://www.cs.uvm.edu/~jauerbac/publications/auerbach_bongard_alife_2012.pdf
Accompanying videos: http://tinyurl.com/ALife13-Videos

The third paper (really just an extended abstract) presents the idea and 
some initial experiments on employing Google Search By Image in lieu of 
interactive evolution (as is done in Picbreeder) to evolve images that 
are interesting to people.  The idea is that Google&#39;s image database 
should indirectly capture what people find interesting and so perhaps 
crafting fitness functions informed by search results from this service 
could evolve interesting images without direct human involvement.  My 
presentation on this paper was awarded Best Presentation in The 
Humanities and ALife track.

Joshua E. Auerbach.  Automated Evolution of Interesting Images. 13th 
International Conference on the Synthesis and Simulation of Living 
Systems (ALife XIII).  East Lansing, MI, July, 2012.

Paper: http://www.cs.uvm.edu/~jauerbac/publications/auerbach_alife_2012b.pdf

Feel free to contact me with any questions, feedback or additional input.

Thanks!
-Josh


